@Xuzz @chronic you really really really need to understand that there is more than one kind of court and more than one kind of ruling
@Xuzz @chronic if I fail to deliver a dozen eggs according to my egg contract, the police are not gonna raid my house & arrest me. Ever.
@Xuzz @chronic all breaking a contract does is entitle the injured party to apply to be compensated with a settlement in civil court.
@Xuzz @chronic Copyright infringement is not contractual.
@Xuzz @chronic if you've broken a contract you've broken a CONTRACT. Contract law is a completely separate thing from criminal law.
@Xuzz @chronic If I tell someone my password of my own free will, I have broken no law, I am merely canceling my right to my Facebook.
@Xuzz @chronic if it were legislating that an employer can't ask the combination to your home safe, it'd be exactly the same concept.
@Xuzz @chronic uhhh this isn't legislating the internet AT ALL. It is legislating the protection of private info from employers.
@Xuzz @chronic All a EULA means is they can cut you off from the service if you break it, or take you to civil court if you REALLY break it
@Xuzz @chronic website EULAs are not laws. They are civil contracts and the penalties for breaking them are purely civil.
@Xuzz @chronic employment laws exist to protect people in a position of weakness and need, they must be very strongly worded.
@Xuzz @chronic generalize the case of employers asking for XYZ password as a requirement of employment. Yes, definitely need a law for this.
